The ggplot package

The ggplot package

The ggplot package allows developing much nicer maps.

world <- ne_countries(scale = "medium")
mediterraneanExtent <- extent(-15, 45, 30, 47.5)
landmassMed <- crop(world, mediterraneanExtent)

# a simple map using plot function
ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = landmassMed, aes(long, lat, group = group))

S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

# a simple colored map with title using ggplot package
ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = landmassMed, fill = "#B9B8B0", colour = "#707070", size = 0.2, 
    aes(long, lat, group = group)) + ggtitle("Southern European coastlines") + xlab("Longitude") + 
    ylab("Latitude")

S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

# making an object for latter representation and manipulation
mapSouthernEurope <- ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = landmassMed, fill = "#B9B8B0", colour = "#707070", 
    size = 0.2, aes(long, lat, group = group))
mapSouthernEurope

S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

# adding information to existing object
mapSouthernEurope <- mapSouthernEurope + ggtitle("Southern European coastlines") + xlab("Longitude") + 
    ylab("Latitude")
mapSouthernEurope

# load data for the bivalve mollusc (Abra alba)
distributionRecords <- read.table("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";", dec = ".", 
    header = T)

# adding information to existing object
mapCoral <- mapSouthernEurope + geom_point(data = distributionRecords, aes(x = Lon, y = Lat), 
    color = "#9A3B04") + ggtitle("Distribution of Paramuricea clavata")
mapCoral

S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

# load and crop raster data
maxSST <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Present Temperature LtMax.tif")
maxSST <- crop(maxSST, mediterraneanExtent)

# Transform raster data to a data.frame
maxSST <- as.data.frame(maxSST, xy = T)
colnames(maxSST) <- c("x", "y", "value")

mapSouthernEurope + geom_tile(data = maxSST, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = value)) + scale_fill_gradient(low = "cyan", 
    high = "red")

S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

# an orthographic projection map is a perspective (or azimuthal) projection.
ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = world, fill = "#B9B8B0", colour = "#707070", size = 0.2, aes(x = long, 
    y = lat, group = group)) + scale_y_continuous(breaks = (-2:2) * 30) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = (-4:4) * 
    45) + coord_map("orthographic", orientation = c(50, 0, 0))

S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

The leaflet package

The leaflet package

Leaflet is a powerful javascript based tool that can be used to create interactive maps - like google maps. Get more information at: https://nceas.github.io/oss-lessons/publishing-maps-to-the-web-in-r/publishing-maps-to-the-web-in-r.html

distributionRecords <- read.table("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";", dec = ".", 
    header = T)
colnames(distributionRecords)
## [1] "X"              "Species"        "Location"       "Year"          
## [5] "Lon"            "Lat"            "Depth"          "Main.reference"
m <- leaflet()
m <- addTiles(m)
m <- addCircleMarkers(m, lng = distributionRecords[, "Lon"], lat = distributionRecords[, "Lat"], 
    radius = 4, color = "Red", stroke = FALSE, fillOpacity = 1)
S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

m
S4 // Better maps with ggplot and leaflet

mpa <- shapefile("Data/vectorShapefiles/noTakeMPA/MPA.shp")
m <- addPolygons(m, data = mpa, color = "Black", stroke = 2, weight = 3)
m
